definition.value: An amide formed between 6-aminopenicillin and butylamine.
A formamide that is the D-enantiomer of N-formylkynurenine.
A glycine carrying an N-phenyl substituent.

An N-acetyl-beta-D-glycosaminyl glycopeptide consisting of an N-acetyl-beta-D-glycosaminyl-(1->4)-N-acetylmuramoyl moiety attached to the amino terminus of the pentapeptide L-Ala-gamma-D-Glu-N(6)-(beta-D-Asp)-L-Lys-D-Ala-D-Ala via an amide linkage.
The (3R)-cis-diastereomer of 3-hydroxy-L-proline.
An acyl group formed from nucleophilic cleavage of the beta-lactam ring of 6-formamidopenicillanic acid.
A disaccharide formed between beta-D-galactose and D-gluconic acid.
Morpholine substituted at nitrogen by a 2-nitrobutyl group.
A C-nitro compound that is a bismorpholine consisting of two morpholinomethyl groups bonded to C-1 of 1-nitropropane.
An amino acid with a structure in which a phenyl ring is bonded to the alpha-carbon of glycine.
A mucopolysaccharide consisting of dermatan with sulfate substituents at the 6'-position of the N-acetylgalactosamines.
An N-sulfonated monobactam antibiotic.
A a methoxyisoflavone that is a 7-methoxyisoflavone compound arising from enzyme-mediated epoxidation/cyclisation of 7-O-methylluteone.
A second generation cephalosporin antibiotic.
A flavanone 7-O-beta-D-glucoside having a beta-L-rhamnosyl residue attached at the 2-position of the glucose ring.

A third-generation cephalosporin antibiotic, bearing a 2-(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)-2-(methoxyimino)acetyl]amino group at the 7beta-position and a [(1-methyl-1H-tetrazol-5-yl)sulfanyl]methyl group at the 3-position.
A monoester of glycerophosphoric acid where R is an organyl group.
The  monocarboxylic acid anion formed by deprotonating carumonam at the carboxyl proton.
A glycerophosphoethanolamine having an unspecified O-acyl substituent at the 1-position of the glycerol fragment.
The monocarboxylic acid anion formed by deprotonating cefuzonam at the carboxyl oxygen.
A dimeric cyclic ketone arising from enzymic oxidation of 2,6-dimethoxyphenol.
Catechol carrying a pentadecenyl substituent at position 3.
The monocarboxylic acid anion formed by deprotonating ceftizoxime at the carboxyl oxygen.
The 2-dehydro derivative of D-galactose.

A monocarboxylic acid that is phenylacetic acid carrying a 4-methoxy substituent. It is used as an intermediate for pharmaceuticals and other organic synthesis. It has been found to inhibit the germination of cress and lettuce seeds.
An aminopyrimidine in which the pyrimidine ring bears amino and hydroxy substituents at positions 2 and 4, respectively.
A benzylic group having methoxy substituents at the 3- and 4-positions on the phenyl ring.

Any member of a group of synthetic antibiotics, similar to cephems but with carbon substituted for the sulfur; all possessing an acylated amine functionality at C-6 and (S,R) stereochemistry at C-6 and C-7.
A benzothiazole consisting of a benzene ring fused to an isothiazole.
Any member of the oxacephem sub-group of cephem antibiotics, in which the thiaazabicyclo moiety of the cephalosporins is replaced by an oxaazabicyclo moiety, and  where R3 is -H or -OCH3.
An alpha-D-galactoside having a methyl substituent at the anomeric position.
An organyl group consisting of a phenyl ring having methoxy substituents at the 2- and 3-position and a (2,4-diaminopyrimidin-5-yl)methyl group at the  5-position.
The anion of cefmenoxime.
A keto-disaccharide consisting of alpha,alpha-trehalose with the keto group at the 3-position.
A trisaccharide consisting of sucrose having an alpha-D-glucopyranosyl residue attached at the 4-position of the glucose ring.
The furanose form of 2-deoxy-D-ribose 5-phosphate.
A trisaccharide consisting of three beta-(1->3)-linked D-glucopyranose units with undefined stereochemistry at the reducing end.
A tryptamine compound having an acetyl substituent attached to the side-chain amino function.

Any one of a large family of chemically related mycotoxins with a structure based on a sesquiterpene skeleton. The most important structural features causing the biological activities of trichothecenes are a 12,13-epoxy ring, the presence of hydroxy or acetyl groups at appropriate positions on the trichothecene nucleus and the structure and position of the side-chain.
An amino acid amide amide in which N-butylglycine and 2-chloro-6-methylaniline have combined to form the amide bond; used as a local anaesthetic (amide caine).
A pyruvic acid having a 5-benzyloxyindol-3-yl group at the 3-position.
The anion of 3-(5-benzyloxyindol-3-yl)pyruvic acid.
A pyruvic acid derivative having a 3-fluoro substituent.
The anion of 3-fluoropyruvic acid.
A nine-carbon straight-chain 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid.
The hydrochloride salt of monoethylglycinexylidide.
